data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages. MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions that tell you *what* went wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    // No built-in "all match" assertion — Assert.IsTrue is fine here,
    // but give it a message:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Instead of .Single() + Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` | Failure says "expected 3, found N" |
| `.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Failure says "expected 1, found N" |

Generic `Assert.IsTrue` only says `"Expected: true, Actual: false"` — specialized assertions pinpoint the problem immediately.
